"{\n  \"correct\": \"no\",\n  \"explanation\": \"The replace() function does not modify the original DataFrame by default. To modify the original DataFrame, the inplace parameter should be set to True. However, in this case, the code is trying to replace values in a Series (df['l2']), not the entire DataFrame, so the operation is performed on the Series but the result is not assigned back to the Series. As a result, the changes are lost.\",\n  \"patch\": \"8c8\\n< df['l2'].replace(to_replace=r'^\\\\d+$', value=0, regex=True)\\n---\\n> df['l2'] = df['l2'].replace(to_replace=r'^\\\\d+$', value=0, regex=True)\\n\"\n}"